{"id": "duc04-testb-23:8#26", "contents": "The decline in exports will trim the growth of the American economy, and was a factor in the Federal Reserve's decision to lower interest rates. Administration officials are portraying the numbers as a warning sign, but not a crisis. The biggest deterioration in the American trade balance in August came in Mexico, where the peso has weakened markedly. Exports to Mexico have remained unchanged, but imports from Mexico have increased, mainly automobiles and automotive parts. In contrast, America's trade surplus with Brazil barely budged, but there is fear that it might be imperiled. The rising trade deficit has barely caused a ripple on Capitol Hill, except in regions where the steel industry is strong, with major steel companies charging that Asian nations are dumping products on the American market at prices well below their costs."}
